1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:05,280
In this course so far, we've already touched briefly on parameters and arguments.

2

00:00:05,280  -->  00:00:08,400
You've already been using these concepts in your Python code,

3

00:00:08,400  -->  00:00:09,940
whether you realize it or not.

4

00:00:09,940  -->  00:00:12,400
Let's dive a bit deeper into these concepts and

5

00:00:12,400  -->  00:00:15,140
start by distinguishing parameters from arguments.

6

00:00:15,140  -->  00:00:17,600
Although they're often used interchangeably,

7

00:00:17,600  -->  00:00:20,540
they actually refer to different concepts in programming.

8

00:00:20,540  -->  00:00:23,340
Parameters are like placeholders that you

9

00:00:23,340  -->  00:00:26,900
define in the function signature when you set up the function.

10

00:00:26,900  -->  00:00:31,140
They are the names you give to data that your function will use,

11

00:00:31,140  -->  00:00:35,140
much like empty plates ready to be filled with food at the dinner table.

12

00:00:35,140  -->  00:00:39,410
Think of these as the placeholder inputs that a function will consume.

13

00:00:39,410  -->  00:00:41,460
Arguments, on the other hand,

14

00:00:41,460  -->  00:00:46,160
are the actual values or data that you pass into the function when you call it.

15

00:00:46,160  -->  00:00:50,280
They're like the food you serve on those plates at the dinner party.

16

00:00:50,280  -->  00:00:54,765
These arguments are what the function uses to perform its task.

17

00:00:54,765  -->  00:00:59,860
Think of these as the actual value inputs that a function will use and run with.

18

00:00:59,860  -->  00:01:04,140
Understanding this distinction helps us when it comes to debugging

19

00:01:04,140  -->  00:01:08,570
or reading our code or someone else's code that we didn't write.

20

00:01:08,570  -->  00:01:12,220
When you see a function definition, look for parameters.

21

00:01:12,220  -->  00:01:15,380
When you see a function call, look for arguments.

22

00:01:15,380  -->  00:01:17,500
They represent the bridge between what

23

00:01:17,500  -->  00:01:22,680
the function needs to know and the actual data it works with.
